	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 parent" id="comment-9903" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-9903" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6630f582b43cd26f6a097bb3d1d06617?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://www.domainnoob.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>John Humphrey</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2011/godaddy-hosting-epic-failure-looking-for-a-new-hosting-service/comment-page-1/#comment-9903">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2011-10-08T14:45:20+00:00">October 8, 2011 at 2:45 pm</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>I was happy with DreamHost shared hosting until I started getting a LOT of 500 errors on some WordPress installs. It&#8217;s now common to hit a 500 on a WP or even plugin update, then find yourself in maintenance mode and have to ftp in to delete the .maintenance file. I&#8217;m not really technical but I tried everything they suggested and am running Super Cache. It&#8217;s a memory issue, but the problem is that none of the shared hosting companies will tell you how much memory you get. It would be awesome (and I&#8217;d be happy to chip in) if someone of your technical ability would test a bunch of hosting companies to find out where we can get the most WP &#8216;bang&#8217; for our buck.</p>
</div>

